"1178","Abt 1191":"circa 1191","1218":"1218","1207":"1207","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1191–Abt 1245":"about 1191–about 1245","1191–1245":"1191–1245","1178–1258":"1178–1258","1207–Male":"1207–Deceased","1218–Male":"1218–Deceased","1226–Male":"1226–Deceased","1228–1245":"1228–1245","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1165":"1165","Abt 1226":"about 1226","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1258":"1258","Abt 1245":"about 1245","1224":"1224","about 1207":"about 1207","about 1218":"about 1218","1245":"1245","1178":"1178","Abt 1191":"about 1191","1218":"1218","1207":"1207","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Villiers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villars","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri.","French: habitational name from any of various places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":24,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":33,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Villiers was born about 1191, his father